Yes, you can send an array within an array in a JSON message as part of a WebSocket transmission. JSON allows for nested structures including arrays within arrays (also known as multi-dimensional arrays or nested arrays) in its data format specification. 

Here is an example of how you can include an array within an array in a JSON object:


```json
{
  "data": [
    ["apple", "banana", "cherry"],
    [
      {"name": "John", "age": 30},
      {"name": "Mary", "age": 25},
      {"name": "Joe", "age": 40}
    ]
  ]
}
```

In this example, the outer level of the JSON object has a "data" field, which is an array having 2 elements: one's an array of 3 fruits and the second one has another array of objects with name and age properties.

You can include as many levels of nested arrays or objects as necessary, however, it's important to ensure that the messages sent over a WebSocket don't exceed the maximum size allowed by the WebSocket protocol and are optimized to reduce network traffic as much as possible.

To send multiple requests (one for each two-factor authentication code), you can loop through the list of authentication codes and send a separate HTTP request for each code. Here's an example of what this might look like in JavaScript:

```javascript
// List of two-factor authentication codes
const codes = ["222222", "333333", "444444"];

// Loop through each code and send an HTTP request for each one
codes.forEach((code) => {
  // Create a new XMLHTTPRequest object
  const xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();

  // Set up the request
  xhr.open("POST", "/auth/validate2faForToken");
  xhr.setRequestHeader("Content-Type", "application/x-www-form-urlencoded");

  // Set the two-factor authentication code as a parameter
  const params = `twofactorCode=${code}`;

  // Send the request
  xhr.send(params);
});
```

In this example, we are using the `XMLHttpRequest` object in JavaScript to send a POST request to the `/auth/validate2faForToken` endpoint for each two-factor authentication code in the `codes` array. 

Note that you may need to modify the endpoint URL and message headers to match the requirements of the system you are working with, and you may also need to handle the response from the server in order to determine whether each code was successfully validated or not.
